  <span id="freeText14726690977470104534" style="display:none">Adina: There is a certain segment of readers who are perpetually annoyed by almost any book that is awarded a Booker or wins a Pulitzer Prize. Nobel laureates seem to provoke the same discredit in the view of other readers. Often, these awards are given to books &amp; authors who attempt to elucidate the complex or the abstract, rather than to catalogue the familiar. For that reason, such books/authors often demand more of the reader. <br /><br />I for one see some similarities in Arundhati Roy's <i>God of Small Things</i> &amp; Salman Rusdie's epic novel, <i>Midnight's Children</i>, though Roy's book is far more insular, while Rushdie offers a more comprehensive fictional world view. Both are wonderful tales &amp; both demand a great deal of patience from the reader. I enjoyed your review comments on Roy's novel. Bill</span>
