    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2912836122" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2912836122" />
    <a title="Alex" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/100387236-alex"><img alt="Alex" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1567614515p2/100387236.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2912836122?book_show_action=true">Jul 27, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Alex" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Alex" href="/user/show/100387236-alex">Alex</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2912836122" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1275401078466027330">This is probably one of the most weirdest books I have ever read. I tried reading this when I was 15 and DNF as I got lost amongst the confusing prose.🙃🙃! Ten years later I found the same words compelling and beautiful. It was a mesmerising read for me.<br/><br/>I feel like this book is not for everyone. Some people may feel that it is dragging or may not be able to relate to the plot or the characters.<br/><br/>Seen through the eyes of 7 year old Rahel, this book initially makes the reader believe it is some silly</span>
  <span id="freeText1275401078466027330" style="display:none">This is probably one of the most weirdest books I have ever read. I tried reading this when I was 15 and DNF as I got lost amongst the confusing prose.🙃🙃! Ten years later I found the same words compelling and beautiful. It was a mesmerising read for me.<br /><br />I feel like this book is not for everyone. Some people may feel that it is dragging or may not be able to relate to the plot or the characters.<br /><br />Seen through the eyes of 7 year old Rahel, this book initially makes the reader believe it is some silly child's musings about a world and people she is not yet capable of comprehending. As the reader proceeds further, it becomes a serious read, discussing several social issues that existed in Kerala. It points a finger at caste based discrimination, misogyny, Indian politics. It also mocks at people's tendency to imitate all things Western. Like how Chacko, Rahel's uncle goes abroad for studies, or how Sophie mol, Chacko's daughter ( with a British woman) is treated in a superior way by their relatives when compared to how they treat Rahel and her twin Estha, how knowing English is considered as equivalent to being cultured...etc. The impact of globalisation in India is also indirectly portrayed. For eg. the twins and their family going to the theatre to watch The Sound of Music is one such instance.<br /><br />Here we meet strange characters under Rahel's innocent observation. Even if she is unable to determine how vile or how good someone is, or what role they play in her and Estha's life, the reader can easily realise how things/ people are getting manipulated. There is Ammu, Rahel's and Estha's helpless young mother. There is Chacko, Ammu's elder brother who gets to have modern education from England's Oxford University, who marries an English woman. There is the smart, intelligent and caring Velutha, a lower caste man, who is the son of Ammu's family servant. There is Baby Kochamma, Ammu's aunt who fell in love with a priest and spent her entire life as a spinster. There are several such characters and each of them is portrayed in detail, it's a well written character study.<br /><br />The story is written over a very confusing time line. Rahel's thoughts drift between present and past and some intermediate time periods without any warning. The brilliance is that Roy is able to create total sense and order out of this chaos.<br /><br />I enjoyed the carefree and often funny way in which the twins tried to make sense of their surroundings. Roy has used several literary techniques to make it realistic. I reccomend this book to people who love deep thought provoking prose, a bunch of interesting characters and a look into the Kerala society that existed in the 1960s. I rarely find books by Indian authors that are beautiful as well as intriguing and weird! 😊😊. <br /><br />I just cant get enough of this book!!</span>
  <a data-text-id="1275401078466027330" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


